                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Some issues with dots:<br /><br />1.  Consistent dot dmg requires that necromancer MUST stack them.  This in turn requires that we have to dedicate more spell slots to dmg than other classes.<br /><br />2.  Necromancers have to worry about a wider range of resists, since the dots MUST be stacked to achieve the same amount of dmg as other casters.<br /><br />3.  Issue's in raids where a couple necromancers have decided to use 6 dots to hog all the glory.  Necromancers keep in mind that there are lots of DoT's in general out there.  We aren't the only dot casting class and I've seen in some cases where necromancers using low end dots will block one of my high end dots simply because all the slots are taken.  It really pisses me off when I see a necromancer using a low end dot and it's blocking not only my dots, but one of the druid/shaman stronger dots.  But for my point...Dot dmg is limited because of this.  One of the people in my guild stated it best, "You can't stack dots like nukers can stack DD's".  It doesn't seem to make sense at first but think about it and it does.<br /><br />4.  Failure to supply dots with proper resist modifiers and less aggro.  Lets be honest here, to keep up with nukers, necromancers have to start dots early.  There is a game flaw in this matter that irks me to no end.  This simply means my stuff has to land early....period.  The designers have given Dots long cast times, long tics between dmg, and too much aggro.  Believe me I'm no idiot, I'm perfectly aware of FD'ing off aggro, and I still think that needing to FD should be necessary when stacking, but there needs to be more balance here, even an extra level of subtlety would be welcome.  As for the resist modifiers, I can't afford for a spell to be resisted.  For a necromancer it's always a race against time(especially in strong high dmg groups) to supply sufficient dmg to be helpful.  Zones like PoF and PoE are the worst as they almost null out Fire and Poison spells respectively.  This destroys a necromancers dmg.<br /><br />5.  No cold resist dots...I truly can't believe this one.  After 4 years there is not a SINGLE cold based dot in the game.  Well for the mobs there is, but of course we aren't as important as the mobs.<br /><br />With some of those issues stated above Dot crits would alleviate the problems.  There is no excuse for having zero cold based dots in game.  And if the counters on dots is what causes them to have high aggro then they need to be removed.  I rarely see a mob that tries to cure him/herself of a dot, and when they do they usually cure it with one cast regardless.  I don't necessarily believe dot crits are the only way to achieve better balance with dots, but I do agree that something needs to be done, as they have become underpowered.<br /><br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
